<div id="review_3527760954" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3527760954" />
    <a title="John Mccullough" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/13417829-john-mccullough"><img alt="John Mccullough" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1349487620p2/13417829.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3527760954?book_show_action=true">Sep 06, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="John Mccullough" class="user" itemprop="url" name="John Mccullough" href="/user/show/13417829-john-mccullough">John Mccullough</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover " href="/book/show/8103061-the-human-comedy">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13417829-john-mccullough?shelf=american-literature">american-literature</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13417829-john-mccullough?shelf=ww-ii">ww-ii</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3527760954" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3792019973880188920">In this time of tribulation and chaos, many of us reach for islands of sanity on our shelves. This time I reached for a book I bought very much used about fifty years ago – Saroyan’s classic exposition of hope in his time of tribulation and chaos. Wise choice.<br/><br/>It is Ithaca in the San Joaquin Valley, California (actually Saroyan’s hometown of Fresno), early in WW II. The Macauley family has lost a father to death and a son to the Army. That leaves 3 children at home. Homer, the oldest boy at 14 ye</span>
  <span id="freeText3792019973880188920" style="display:none">In this time of tribulation and chaos, many of us reach for islands of sanity on our shelves. This time I reached for a book I bought very much used about fifty years ago – Saroyan’s classic exposition of hope in his time of tribulation and chaos. Wise choice.<br /><br />It is Ithaca in the San Joaquin Valley, California (actually Saroyan’s hometown of Fresno), early in WW II. The Macauley family has lost a father to death and a son to the Army. That leaves 3 children at home. Homer, the oldest boy at 14 years old, has taken a job as messenger for the telegraph company to pay bills. He delivers many telegrams, the most devastating are telegrams from the War Office that are death notices to family survivors, a very heavy lift for a boy his age, as he doesn’t just drop the telegrams off, but is invited in by the recipients. Yes, a heavy lift.<br /><br />Homer and his 4-year-old brother, Ulysses, interact with other kids, and with adults, but the book keys on Homer and his epiphanies as he enters the adult world, thus a “coming-of-age” book. But it is so much more. It recreates some of the spirit of the US in WW II as I vaguely remember as a young child. Whatever our other differences we were united in our desire to beat the fascist powers that had attacked us or declared war on us.<br /><br />But this is now an historic country that Saroyan describes; it no longer exists. Instead of fighting fascism we are on the brink of becoming a deflated fascist country, divided along so many axes, complete with attacks on the free press, the development of splinter groups resembling Germany’s Brown Shirts and citizens rallying around absolutely bizarre conspiracies as QAnon.<br /><br />The book is bittersweet. It is filled with kind, loving adults who, like Lord Chesterfield, offer advice to Homer when he is perplexed by the horrors created by the adults, among whose ranks he will join in just a few years. How could they do things like this? Why are there so many of “those telegrams” he must personally deliver? As a child the age of Ulysses I remember passing house after house in my Chicago neighborhood with little flags in the windows; the number of stars on the flags represented the number of children who were in the armed services. A silver star meant they were still serving while a gold star meant the child was dead. Some houses had little flags with two or three gold stars. It was so sad to see all these flags in house after house along our walks. Even at that age I knew what the gold color meant.<br /><br />A warning – cynics will find the book nauseatingly sanguine, so don’t even bother. Others who have lived through tragedy and been emotionally and intellectually affected by it, have learned from it, will find common ground with the poor, common people in the book attempting to come to terms with the horrible events they have fallen victim to, and the hope they must cling to in order to retain their sanity.<br /><br />But, it is a good book for our times, in part to give us hope, in part to recall the better souls of what we were and could be again – flawed but miraculous creatures.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3792019973880188920" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

