  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1186245057" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1186245057" />
    <a title="Josh Caporale" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5687551-josh-caporale"><img alt="Josh Caporale" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1431172307p2/5687551.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1186245057?book_show_action=true">Jan 31, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Josh Caporale" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Josh Caporale" href="/user/show/5687551-josh-caporale">Josh Caporale</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1186245057" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7496067630178565624">I first came across William Saroyan&apos;s written work when I was in seventh grade, where a complete section in our book consisted of Saroyan&apos;s shorter works. The first work, and the one that stayed with me the most, was a short work known as &quot;The Telegram,&quot; that was a poignant account where a telegraph messenger named Homer had to deliver the news to a mother that her son was killed in combat. I am sure that I was aware that this story was part of a larger work and years later, I decided to look fo</span>
  <span id="freeText7496067630178565624" style="display:none">I first came across William Saroyan's written work when I was in seventh grade, where a complete section in our book consisted of Saroyan's shorter works. The first work, and the one that stayed with me the most, was a short work known as "The Telegram," that was a poignant account where a telegraph messenger named Homer had to deliver the news to a mother that her son was killed in combat. I am sure that I was aware that this story was part of a larger work and years later, I decided to look for that work. <br /><br />It turned out being part of The Human Comedy, which was a novel set in Ithaca in California during the Second World War, where Homer is the central character growing up during a devastating time, while also living his life like anyone would live their life despite this intense and somewhat nerve-wracking time. Homer lives his mother and siblings, including an older brother, Marcus, that is off at war. His younger brother, Ulysses, gets himself caught up in a lot of issues himself, such as getting stuck in a bear trap at a store. The message to this novel is that despite the horrific situations that are taking place during this particular time period (in this case, World War II), life has to go on for the rest of humanity, which signifies its comedic element.<br /><br />For its time, place, and lens, this novel was outstanding! I feel that this is a novel that can continue being studied for how it captures a moment of history while also paying attention to humanity in general. It assures us the illusion of the life inside and outside of war and how there is a great separation that is unfortunate, but also necessary in allowing life outside of war to remain stable. You are bound to develop a heartfelt connection in the characters in this work for so many reasons and I feel that Saroyan does an outstanding job developing that emotional bond.<br /><br />I wish that this novel was much easier to find, much more available to the general population, and presented much more on curriculums and recommended reading lists. It was the second best novel I read in 2015 for a reason! </span>
  <a data-text-id="7496067630178565624" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


